[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "All"]
[Deal "E:K764.K7.KQJ3.AJ2 J9.AT832.975.854 Q52.J5.A642.QT96 AT83.Q964.T8.K73"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "3NT"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1NT pass 2NT pass 3NT pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 4, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "edcbc1862b8ca27fdbeed2fde4ad146bce223dd1a5491dbf3350e97d275a9048"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/entry_management"]
[Student "S"]
{East is to play 3NT. South leads the \H3, you play dummy's \HJ and North plays the \HQ.

Winners:   \S=0  \H=1  \D=4  \C=1  Total = 6

Unless you want to go down really, really early you had better take your \HK right now. And unless you want to go down almost as early you'd better stay completely away from the \S suit. So that only leaves you the \C suit to get 3 more winners in. North will have to have \CK so you can finesse it. You are also going to have to be smart with entries. Got it?

If North has just \C K x then one finesse, followed by the \CA to drop the \CK and a small \C back to dummy will give you the 4 \C winners you must have. But if North has \C K x x and refuses to cover then you will be able to establish the \Cs but will need an extra dummy entry to enjoy that last winner.

So win the \HK and play the \D K Q. If both defenders follow suit you can afford to overtake your \DJ with dummy's \DA. Now play the \CT and let it ride. If it holds the trick play another \C to your \CJ and then play the \CA, dropping North's \CK.

Enter dummy by playing your \D3 to the \D6 and take your established \C for the ninth trick.

Suppose a defender showed out on the second \D.

With only one outside entry to dummy your choices are limited.

You might play North for \C K x and lead a small to your \CJ, then play \CA.

Or you might try leading the \CQ hoping that North will see this as a time to "cover an honor with an honor".}
[Play "W"]H3

